Many workers will be on furlough this Christmas. Some of them would have also been asked to take a pay cut to keep their company afloat. Being able to fork out money to enjoy the season would be a big ask for these people.
There’s also no denying that thousands of people would be without their loved ones because the pandemic has claimed their lives. So rather than having a day of celebration, we would be having a day of reflection. For some reason, the Christmas vibes seem less exciting, year after year.





Staff and family get-togethers
Christmas can be easily placed on the backburner when safety and lifesaving measures are of the utmost importance. Christmas celebrations are one of the most social gatherings — where people enjoy the staff and family get-togethers.
 It is meant to be the most joyous of times, after all, when humanity blends together their religious faiths in the celebration of Jesus Christ on the day of his birth. At this time of the year, such a state of mind is somewhat absent, dismantled, or eviscerated by Covid-19.
As far as religion is concerned, God has forsaken man at these moments. A thunderous silent call to repentance, rather than celebration. Humanity’s collective compassion seems in a state of attrition, too long in a depreciating spiral.



